column168: THIS SPILL RESULTED FROM THE OVERFILLING OF AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO A CONVENIENCE STORE. THE STORE HAD ORDERED TOO MUCH GAS AND THE DRIVER WAS TOPPING OFF THE TANKS WHEN ANOTHER TRUCK PULLED INTO THE PARKING LOT ON THE OTHER SIDE OF OUR TANKER NEAR OUR VAPOR RECOVERY CONNECTION. OUR DRIVER THOUGHT THE TRUCK WAS GOING TO HIT THE VAPOR HOSE SO HE RAN AROUND TO THE OTHER SIDE OF THE TANK TO WARN THE OTHER DRIVER. OUR DRIVER DID NOT STOP THE DELIVERY BEFORE LEAVING THE FILL POINT AND THE TANK OVERFILLED BEFORE HE GOT BACK. GAS WAS CONTAINED ON BLACKTOP AND CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANTS.THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED THE REFERENCE #9311726 TO THE INCIDENT.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A GASOLINE DELIVERY FROM OUR TANKER TO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK AT A CONVIENCE STORE.  AS BEST AS WE CAN TELL, THE EXTREME COLD WEATHER CAUSED THE CHECK VALVE IN THE UST'S VENT LINE TO STICK CAUSING PRESSURE TO BUILD UP IN THE TANK.  THIS PRESSURE CAUSED THE GAS TO COME OUT AROUND THE VAPOR RECOVERY FIRING.  AFTER THE INITIAL PRESSURE WAS RELEASED, THE VENT SYSTEM WORKED PROPERLY.  THE SPILL WAS CONFINED ON BLACKTOP AND THE NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED REFERENCE #9311793 TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: OUR INVESTIGATION INTO THE SULFUR SPILL INCIDENT WHICH OCCURRED ON TUESDAY, JAN 4, 1994 HAS BEEN COMPLETED. AN EFFORT WAS MADE TO REMOVE THE SULFUR FROM THE ROAD SURFACE, BUT BECAUSE THERE WERE SUCH SMALL AMOUNTS SPILLED AT EACH LOCATION, IT WAS A FUTILE ATTEMPT. AFTER DISCUSSING FURTHER CLEANUP EFFORTS WITH YOUR ENVIRONMENTAL SUPERVISOR, MR. CLYDE WISEMAN, IT WAS DECIDED THAT REMOVING ANY REMAINING SULFUR WAS UNNECESSARY SINCE THE CHARACTERISTICS AND NATURE OF THE PRODUCT POSED NO HEALTH OR ENVIRONMENTAL THREAT. THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS A 3 INCH CLEAN OUT LINE AT THE TOP FRONT OF OUR SULFUR TRAILER. THE TRAILER HAD BEEN CLEANED AND PURGED FOR INTERNAL REPAIRS SEVERAL DAYS PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT AND THE CLEAN OUT CAP WAS INADVERTENTLY LEFT UNSCREWED AFTER REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED. OUR DRIVER FAILED TO NOTICE THE UNSCREWED CAP DURING HIS PRE-TRIP VEHICLE INSPECTION AND LOADED FOR A DELIVERY TO COLGATE-PALMOLIVE IN JEFFERSONVILLE, INDIANA. HE DROVE TO THE INTERSECTION OF ROUTE 4 AND INTERSTATE 64 BEFORE REALIZING AND CORRECTING THE PROBLEM. INITIAL REPORTS WERE THAT SULFUR HAD SPILLED AT TWO LOCATIONS INSIDE YOUR PLANT AND AT THE INTERSECTION OF RAND AVENUE AND ROUTE 111. AFTER FURTHER INVESTIAGION HOWEVRE, ADDITIONAL SPILLS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE INTERSTATE 70 EAST AND ROUTE 4 SOUTH OFF-RAMPS, AT THE INTERSECTION OF ROUTE 4 SOUTH AND ROUTE 50 WEST AND AT THE ROUTE 4 SOUTH AND INTERSTATE 64 EAST ON-RAMP. THE QUANTITY OF SULFUR SPILLED AT ALL LOCATIONS WAS ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN 10 GALLONS TOTAL. OF HT ETWO EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT, ONE HAS BEEN DISCHARGED AND THE OTHER HAS BEEN REPRIMANDED.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT HIS DESTINATION.  THE RECEIVER ADVISED THAT THERE WAS AMPLE STORAGE TO ACCEPT THE MATERIAL BEING DELIVERED. OUR DRIVER PULLED OVER, ISOLATED AND SECURED THE UNIT, AND INITIATED EMERGENCY NOTIFICATION PROCEDURES.  LOCAL EMERGENCY SERVICE FOR THE AREA WERE CONTACTED AS WELL AS THE SHIPPER. LARCO ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS CONTRACTED FOR SITE REMEDIATION.

AS LOAD WAS BEING PUMPED OFF THE HOSE SUCKED IN AIR AND JERKED CAUSING CAM EAR TO COME LOOSE SPRAY APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF BLACK OIL ON THE DIKE WALL. AT THE CUSTOMERS DOCK, OUR DRIVER WAS ROLLING THE CARBOY ON THE BOTTOM EDGES, WHEN ONE SLIPPED OUT OF HIS HANDS.  IT FELL TO THE FLOOR OF VAN TRAILER AND THE BUNG(CLOSURE) POPPED OUT. column168: LOCAL DRIVER WAS AT THE CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVING DOCK MAKING A FREIGHT DELIVERY.  THE CONSIGNEE'S FORKLIFT OPERATOR DROVE A FORKLIFT INTO THE TRAILER TO TAKE OFF A PORTABLE TANK CONSIGNED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS BACKING OUT OF THE TRAILER WITH THE PORTABLE TANK WHEN THE REAR WHEELS OF THE FORKLIFT CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE DOCK PLATE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  EVIDENTLY THE SUDDEN BUMPING ACTION CAUSED THE PORTABLE TANK TO BOUNCE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH THE IMPACT AND BELOW FREEZING TEMPERATURE CAUSING THE METAL DRAIN VALVE TO SNAP RIGHT OFF ALLOWING THE LIQUID INSIDE TO SPILL OUT.  FORKLIFT OPERATORS MUST EXERCISE CAUTION WHEN HANDLING PORTABLE TANKS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TO ENSURE NO DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINER TAKES PLACE.

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR-SEMI CARGO TANK TRAILER WAS UNLOADING LEADED GASOLINE FROM THE CARGO TANK TRAILER INTO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. APPARENTLY THE CARGO TANK COMPARTMENT CONTAINED MORE PRODUCTS THEN THE UNDERGROUND STORGAE TANK WOULD HOLD.  WHEN THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK FILLED, THE FUEL BACKED UP INTO THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM OF THE CARGO TANK TRAILER.  WHEN THE DRIVER UNHOOKED THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE THE FUEL FLOWED ONTO THE DRIVEWAY SURFACE OF THE CIRCLE K SERVICE STATION.  THE SPILLED FUEL WAS CONTAINED ON THE DRIVEWAY.  IT DID NOT FLOW ONTO A STORM DRAIN OR SEWER DRAIN NOR ONTO GROUND.  THE SHOW LOW FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE FUEL HAD EVAPORATED PRIOR TO THEIR ARRIVAL. SPILL PREVENTION TRAINING WILL BE GIVEN TO THE VEHICLE DRIVER IN THE NEAR FUTURE.

column168: THE INSURED HAD ARRIVED TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL NUMBER TWO/FURNACE OIL TO BE UTILIZED TO HEAT THE GRADE SCHOOL.  THE INSURED DRIVER WENT IN WITH THE BUILDING'S JANITOR TO CHECK THE AMOUNT OF FUEL IN THEIR UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK TO SEE IF THEY COULD POSSIBLY TAKE ANOTHER COMPLETE COMPARTMENT OF FUEL FROM THE TRAILER INTO THE GRADE SCHOOL'S STORAGE TANK.  THE JANITOR AND DRIVER WENT INSIDE TO CHECK READINGS.  THEY WERE INSIDE A SHORT TIME WHEN SOMEONE YELLED THAT THERE WAS FUEL BEING SPILLED BEHIND THE SCHOOL AND THEY WENT IMMEDIATELY TO INVESTIGATE.   THE INSURED'S TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE GOING UP A SLIGHT GRADE AND THE TIRES WERE HOT FROM BEING ON THE ROAD.  THE INSURED SET THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER BRAKE AND WAD LETTING GRAVITY FLOW PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER INTO THE UNDERGROUND TANK.  THE TIRES MELTED TO THE SNOW AND THEN THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER SLID APPROXIMATELY 10 FEET DOWN THE GRADE.  THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH HOSE AND IT BROKE THE VALVES AND PIPE FROM UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER, RESULTING IN AN UNCONTROLLED, INSTANTANEOUS DUMPING OF PRODUCT FROM THE INSURED'S TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND.

CUSTOMER CLAIMED TANK VALVE WAS CLOSED SO OUR DRIVER PROCEEDED AND TURNED OFF HIS TRUCK PUMP.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTICED PRODUCT BACK FLUSHING THROUGH HIS HOSE AND ON TO HIS DRIP PAN.  HE IMMEDIATELY GOT BACK INTO HIS TRUCK AND STARTED HIS TRUCK PUMP WHICH PUSHED THE PRODUCT INTO THE TANK AGAIN. ONCE AGAIN HE ASKED THE CUSTOMER TO CLOSE OFF THE TANK VALVE, THE CUSTOMER ACKNOWLEDGE THAT THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND OUR DRIVER SHUT HIS TRUCK PUMP OFF AGAIN.  THIS TIME THE PROCEDURE WORKED JUST LIKE IT WAS SUPPOSED TO. IN CONCLUSION, WE DETERMINED THAT THE CUSTOMER DID NOT HAVE HIS VALVE COMPLETELY CLOSED ON THE TANK THE FIRST TIME.

HYDROGEN TRAILER (SN 613703) WAS RETURNING EMPTY FROM KENNEDY SPACE CENTER TO NEW ORLEANS, LA. UPON DEPARTURE AT 12 NOON, THE INTERNAL VESSEL PRESSURE WAS 8 PSIG.  AT THE FIRST SAFETY CHECK, THE PRESSURE HAD RISED TO 20 PSIG.  AT THE SECOND SAFETY CHECK IN LEE, FLORIDA, THE PRESSURE HAD RISEN TO 42 PSIG.  AT THIS TIME, THE DRIVERS RECEIVED INSTRUCTION TO MOVE THE TRAILER TO A SAFE LOCATION AND CONDUCT A CONTROLLED VENTNG TO 30 PSIG. THE PRESSURE REMAINED AT AN ACCEPTABLE LEVEL FOR THE REMAINDER OF THE TRIP.  AN INSPECTION OF THE UNIT REVEALS THAT THE RISE IN PRESSURE WAS DUE TO MOISTURE BEING RELEASED INTO THE ANNULAR SPACE FROM INTERNAL GEDDERS. THE TRAILER WAS PUT OUT OF SERVICE AND CORRECTIVE MAINTENANCE WAS PERFORMED TO REMOVE ALL EXCESS MOISTURE FROM THE ANNULAR SPACE.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUNICY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S CLEVELAND SERVICE CENTER LOCATED IN CLEVELAND, OHIO.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PALLET OF BOXED CONTAINING FLOURESCENT LIGHT BULBS SHIFTED IN TRANSIT CRUSHING A BOX ON THE BOTTOM LAYER OF THE PALLET RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF GALSS AND MERCURY DEBRIS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE CAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, SWEPT UP THE DEBRIS AND REPACKAGED THE REMAINING FLOURESCENT LIGH BULBS.  ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO THE REPACKAGED CONTAINER AND WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE DRIVER INSPECTED THE LOAD AND FOUND THE INDIVIDUAL BOXES SHRINK WRAPPED TO THE PALLET AND A LOAD LOCKED IN PLACE.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, ADDITIONAL LOAD LOCKS WILL BE USED WHEN SHIPPING PALLETS CONTAINING BOXES TO PREVENT A LOAD SHIFT.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN VITRO CORPORATION LOCATED AT 1400 GEORGIA AVENUE IN SILVER SPRING, MD TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALITMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE ESTINATION FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM SEAM OF ONE OF THE DRUMS ONTO FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEANUP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: THE MOBILE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING 260 GALLONS OF SUPER UNLEADED INTO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK AT THE SERVICE STATION.  TOWARD THE END OF THE DELIVERY THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK BECAME EXCESSIVE AND BEGAN COMING BACK UP THE FILL PIPE.  THE DRIVER QUICKLY SHUT THE VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK, BUT THE PRESSURE CONTINUED TO FORCE PRODUCT INTO THE SPILL TANK, BUT THE PRESSURE CONTINUED TO FORCE PRODUCT INTO THE SPILL BUCKET AROUND THE FILL PIPE.  AS THE LEVEL IN THE SPILL BUCKET ROSE THE GASOLINE STARTED ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD SURROUNDING THE FILL AREA.  THE DRIVER QUICKLY PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AROUND THE AREA AND TRANSFERRED THE DELIVERY HOSE TO THE SPECIAL UNLEADED TANK TO EMPTY THE HOSE.  UPON DOING SO, THE PRESSURE FROM THE SUPER UNLEADED TANK WAS RELIEVED AND THE FLOW OF PRODUCT CEASED.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED AS A PRECAUTION AND A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR DISPATCHED TO REMOVED ICE AND SLUSH FROM A NEARBY SEWER JUST AS PRECAUTION.  THERE WAS MINIMAL CLEAN UP REQUIRED.  IT WAS LATER FOUND THAT A VENTING PROBLEM HAD OCCURED AND THE PROBLEM WAS CORRECTED.

column168: THIS LETTER IS A FOLLOW-UP REPORT TO OUR PHONE NOTIFICATION REGARDING THE ABOVE REFERENCED INCIDENT WHICH OCCURRED ON JANUARY 27, 1994 INVOLVING A SPILL OF PROPYLENE OXIDE (CAS375-56-9).  PROPYLENE OXIDE IS A 302(A) EXTREMELY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE.  THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS APPROXIMATELY 50 POUNDS.  THE INITIAL PHONE NOTIFICATION INDICATED A SPILL OF ABOUT 1200 POUNDS WHICH WAS BASED ON A LEAK WITH AN ESTIMATED OPENING BETWEEN THE GASKET AND THE FLANGE OF 1/32 OF AN INCH.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION AFTER THE INCIDENT WAS OVER THE ACTUAL GAP WAS TESTED WITH A 0.001 INCH FEELER GAUGE AND FOUND TO BE SMALLER WHICH RESULTED IN THE LOWER QUANTITY RELEASED.  THIS WAS ALSO CONFIRMED BY LATER DISCUSSIONS WITH PERSONNEL WHO RESPONDED TO THE LEAK.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED ABOUT 9:05 A.M. ON JANUARY 27, 1994 AND WAS STOPPED BY ABOUT 9:20 A.M. THE INCIDENT WAS FULLY TERMINATED AT 10:30 A.M.  WILL COUNTY EMA WAS NOTIFIED AT 9:15 A.M. WITH FOLLOW-UP CALLS AT 10:20 AND 11:00 A.M. ILLINOIS EMA WAS NOTIFIED AT 10:55 A.M. THE NRC WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.  THE LEAK OCCURRED BETWEEN TWO GASKETED FLANGES THAT WERE BOLTED TOGETHER BY STEPAN OPERATORS BEFORE UNLOADING THE PROPYLENE OXIDE FROM RAIL CAR UTLX 900762.  THE GASKET IS LOCATED BETWEEN A FLANGED FLEXIBLE SECTION OF PIPE AND THE FLANGE ON A SOLID SECTION OF PIPE WHICH IS THEN ATTACHED TO THE RAILCAR FLANGE.  THE LEAK OCCURRED ON THE GASKETED SECTION AWAY FROM THE RAIL CAR AND NOT THE FLANGE CONNECTED DIRECTLY TO THE RAIL CAR.  WHILE THE RELEASE WAS LIQUID THE MATERIAL HAS SOME VAPOR PRESSURE WHICH RESULTED IN PRECAUTIONARY ACTION OF CONTACTING THE RAILROADS AND STOPPING TRAFFIC ON THE MAIN LINE WHICH WAS DIRECTLY DOWNWIND ABOUT 100 FEET AWAY.  THE RELEASE WAS MITIGATED BY USE OF WATER SPRAYS WHICH REACT WITH THE CHEMICAL TO FORM PROPYLENE GLYCOL WHICH IS NOT HAZARDOUS.  THE RUNOFF WAS DIRECTED TOWARDS THE PROCESS DRAIN WHICH FLOWS TO AN ONSITE WASTEWATER TREATMENT PLANT.  THE GROUND AREA UNDER THE RAIL CAR WAS COMPLETELY COVERED WITH ICE PRIOR TO THE SPILL DUE TO THE ICE STORM THE PREVIOUS NIGHT.  THIS RESULTED IN NO MATERIAL CONTACTING THE GROUND.  ACTIONS TAKEN TO RESPOND AND CONTAIN THE RELEASE INCLUDED THE OPERATORS DONING PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND SHUTTING THE VALVE ON THE RAIL CAR BEFORE THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  ALSO, WATER WAS USED TO MITIGATE ANY VAPOR AND REDUCE THE HAZARDOUS CHEMICAL TO A NON-HAZARDOUS LIQUID.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS REQUIRED. DUE TO THE SMALL AMOUNT OF THE RELEASE THERE WERE NO KNOWN OR ANTICIPATED HEALTH RISKS TO THE PUBLIC.  PLANT PERSONNEL RESPONDING TO THE AREA OF THE LEAK WERE WEARING FULL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.  STEPAN EMPLOYEES APPROXIMATELY 400 PEOPLE AND THE SIC CODE FOR THIS OPERATION IS 2843.  IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS OR NEED FURTHER INFORMATION, PLEASE CONTACT ME AT (815) 727-4944.

THE RECEIVER'S GAUGE WASN'T WORKING PROPERLY CAUSING OPERATORS TO BELIEVE THE TANK WAS EMPTY ENOUGH TO ACCEPT LOAD.  OVERFLOW COMPONENTS MALFUNCTIONED ALSO CAUSING THE SPILL.  TOP OF TANK RUPTURED WHEN TANK FILLED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.  PLANT CLEAN UP UNIT RESPONDED TO SPILL.

RUBBER LINING FAILURE. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY PLANT PERSONNEL.  VETTERS BAG USED TO STOP LEAK.  THE DAMAGE TO THE STEEL SHELL IN THE MISSISSIPPI CHEMICAL EXPRESS TRAILER WE INSPECTED TODAY WAS CAUSED BY A PUNCTURE IN THE RUBBER.  THIS PUNCTURE WAS DIRECTLY BELOW THE MANWAY OPENING AND COULD HAVE BEEN FROM A SHARP "DIP STICK" OR FROM SOMETHING DROPPED INTO THE TRAILER.  WHATEVER PUNCTURED THE LINING HAD A FAIR AMOUNT OF FORCE BEHIND IT AS IT PENETRATED TWO LAYERS OF THE 3/16" SOFT GUM RUBBER.  THE CRACKING IN THE HARDER SURFACE OF THE RUBBER AS A BUBBLE FORMED IN IT.  THIS BUBBLE WAS FORMED BY THE RESIDUE OF THE REACTION BETWEEN THE TRAILER'S CONTENTS AND THE STEEL SHELL.  THE REST OF THE RUBBER LINING SEEMS TO BE IN GOOD SHAPE.  WE WILL SPARKTEST THE REST OF THE LINING WHEN THE TRAILER RETURNS FROM THE STEEL REPAIR SHOP.

THEY THEN PUT DOWN SPEEDI DRY ON THE REMAINING OIL AND FOLLOWED THE SAME PROCEDURE AS WITH THE SAND WHICH WAS THEN TAKEN TO AMERICAN RECYCLING IN CHARLTON, MA FOR DISPOSAL. JACK GRAY TRANSPORT, INC. NOTIFIED NATIONAL RESPONSE, REPORT #215607 AND MA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, REPORT, #4-10188. COPIES OF THE REPORT WERE MAILED TO THE AGENCIES INVOLVED.

INSPECTION DEVELOPED SMALL LEAK AREA PACKING GLAND NUT GAUGING DEVICE.  GAUGING DEVICE WAS EXTREMELY RUSTY AND PACKING GLAND NUT WAS IMPOSSIBLE TO REMOVE TO ADD PACKING MATERIAL.  NOTED BAD ORDER CAR NOTICE WIRED TO CHAIN AFFIXED TO PROTECTIVE COVER ON GAUGING DEVICE.  THIS NOTICE WAS NOT FILLED OUT.  IT APPEARS PRIOR PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED WITH THIS TANK CAR.  TIGHTENED PACKING GLAND NUT WHICH REDUCED LEAK TO ALMOST NONDETECT.  DUE TO CONDITION OF GAUGING DEVICE DECISION WAS MADE TO RETURN CAR ORIGIN FOR UNLOADING AND REPAIRS.  THIS WAS HANDLED UNOCAL PERSONNEL TOM KLEIN AND BRUCE WALKER, HEDGES, WA.  TRACEY JACKSON, CHEMTREC, FURNISHED DETAILS.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY, RECEIVED A PAGE FROM MARTIN VASQUEZ, SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LOCAL INDUSTRY WITH A LEAKING TANK CAR.  DEVELOPED THAT CLOROX (INDUSTRY TRACK 10-723) HAD FIVE TANK CARS ON THEIR DOCK TRACK, AND ONE OF THEIR PLANT PERSONNEL, WHILE CLEANING THE DOCK AREA, NOTICED A CHLORINE ODOR.  UPON CHECKING THE TANK CARS STORED AT THE DOCK, CHLOROX PERSONNEL LOCATED A SLIGHT VAPOR EMITTING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE ON ONE OF THE TANK CARS.  THEY APPLIED A CAP FROM A CHLORINE "C" KIT OVER THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WHICH CURTAILED THE LEAK.  PLANT PERSONNEL REQUESTED THE TANK CAR BE SWITCHED FROM THE DOCK TRACK TO THEIR TANK CAR UNLOADING RACK WHICH IS SITUATED INSIDE A SECURE ENCLOSURE.

column168: CAR DEDICATED TO CARRIER USE, CONTAINS RESIDUE; IS IN TEMPORARY STORAGE. INSPECTION BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT DECHANT DISCLOSED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET, WITH VERY SLIGHT POOLING BENEATH RAILCAR.  ALL LEAKAGE WAS STOPPED BY TIGHTENING BOTTOM OUTLET CAP APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TURN.

ROUTINE INSPECTION BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT DECHANT DISCLOSED PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF RAILCAR, WITH VERY SLIGHT POOLING ON GROUND.  SOURCE OF LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE CENTER MANWAY OF THE THREE LOCATED AT THE TOP OF THE RAILCAR.  MANWAY COVER IS EQUIPPED WITH 4 SWING BOLTS, ONE OF WHICH WAS SECURE, TWO WERE HAND TIGHT, AND ONE WAS COMPLETELY DISENGAGED. THIS ARRANGEMENT UTILIZES AND O"-RING" TYPE GASKET, WHICH WAS DISPLACED AT THE POINT OF THE DISENGAGED SWING BOLT, DIRECTLY OPPOSITE THE HINGE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  VISUAL INSPECTION DISCLOSED CAR LOADED TO CAPACITY' A SLIGHT WHITE FOAMING WAS NOTED ON THE SURFACE OF THE LOAD. GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION; WAS RESEATED AND ALL SWING BOLTS SECURED.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS FOUND TO BE SECURE.  THE SLIGHT AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE THAT POOLED ON THE GROUND WAS DILUTED BY MELTING SNOW, WITH NO CLEANUP WARRANTED.  THE IOWA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES ASSIGNED SPILL NUMBER 01114-SM-1505 TO THIS INCIDENT.  TWO MISSING PLACARDS WERE REPLACED ON RAILCAR, PRIOR TO RELEASING FOR MOVEMENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ROUTINE INSPECTION BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT DECHANT DISCLOSED PRODUCT DRIPPING SLOWLY FROM BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  VALVE OPERATING LEVER FULLY CLOSED AND UNDER PROTECTION OF SEAL KERR-MCGEE LA-05437.  THREADS ON BOTTOM OUTLET WERE WET WITH PRODUCT, AS WAS ENTIRE OUTLET CAP.  DRIPPING STOPPED WHEN CAP WAS TIGHTENED 3/4 TURN, USING 36" WRENCH.  TOP UNLOADING VALVE COVER FOUND FULLY OPENED, BUT DID NOT CONTRIBUTE TO LEAK.  WAS CLOSED FOLLOWING INSPECTION.  ALL SPILLAGE DRIPPED ONTO A SINGLE CROSSITE BENEATH RAILCAR, WITH LEAKAGE RATE SLOW ENOUGH TO ALLOW EVAPORATION PRIOR TO ANY POOLING.  NO CLEANUP REQUIRED.  IOWA DEPT OF NATURAL RESOURCES SPILL #01114-SM-1505 ASSIGNED.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JEFF MILLER, MANAGER, TRAIN OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT TANK CAR GCTX 413134 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL YARD SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE EAST END OF YARD TRACK #10 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  THE CAR ARRIVED YERMO IN THE LZN-59 AT HOURS ON MONDAY, JANUARY 3, 1994, AFTER BEING RECEIVED FROM THE ATSF INTERCHANGE AT BARSTOW, CALIFORNIA.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND BAFFLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND THE RUPTURE DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON BS&B DISC.  THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATION WERE NOT MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, OR TO THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES.

column168: S/A, BALLANCE WHILE MAKING INSPECTIONS OF TANKCARS FOUND TANKCAR. UTLX-88471 LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE.  THE OUTSIDE TEMPERTURE WAS LOW.  THE TANKCAR PRESSURE WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE 95 POUNDS WHICH WAS BELOW THE ACTIVATION PRESSURE FOR THE SAFETY RELEIF VALVE.  THE LIQUID LEVEL WAS ALSO CHECKED AND FOUND TO HAVE 23 INCHES OF OUTAGE.  BOB STINE AND DEAN WHITELEY WERE CALLED TO ASSIST IN CHECKING THE O-RINGS.  THEY ARRIVED AND BEGAN THE INSPECTION.  THE O-RINGS WERE FOUND TO BE BAD AND WERE REPLACED.  PAUL SMITH WITH CHEVRON AND FLORES WITH CHEMTREC WERE ADVISED.  JOHN ROYLAND WITH STOCKTON FIRE WAS ALSO ON SCENE.

column168: PERSON DELIVERING FREIGHT TO LOADING DOCK ACCIDENTLY PUNCTURED ONE OF THREE JERRICANS.  THE PUNCTURE WAS CAUSED BY AN EXPOSED NAIL ON THE WOODEN SKID USED TO STORE THE FREIGHT.  UPON REALIZING THE EXTENT OF DAMAGE, THE WAREHOUSE AGENT TURNED THE JERRICAN UPSIDE DOWN TO STOP THE LEAKING AND EVACUATED THE AREA.  AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT AND AS PART OF OUR ROUTINE TRAINING, ALL STAFF WILL BE PUT THROUGH AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TRAINING.  THE INDIVIDUALS INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT WERE ALL AERLINGUS EMPLOYEES.  THEIR NAMES ARE PATRICK CONWAY, MARTIN KELLY, AND THOMAS O'TOOLE.

AS THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A TURN, THE DRUM ON HIS TRAILER SLID.  THE DRUM STRUCK THE BOTTOM FORKS OF A DRUM TRUCK, CAUSING A LEAK.  THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THE LEAK AS HE PULLED INTO THE SEABOARD FARMS DOCK.  THE DRIVER ADJUSTED THE POSITION OF THE DRUM TO PROVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE.  THE CALLED THE SERVICE CENTER WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER (NIAGARA NATIONAL, 2160-C HILLS AVENUE, ATLANTA, GA. ASK FOR ARTHUR DUTTON).  PER INSTRUCTIONS, THE LEAKED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH APPROPRIATE MATERIAL. THE DRUM AND ALL RESIDUE WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR PROPER USE AND HANDLING.  THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED IN THE PROPER PROCEDURE FOR BLOCKING AND BRACKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR TRANSPORT.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE INNER GLASS BOTTLES LID POPPED OFF IN HANDLING.  AN EMPLOYEE, WOODSON SKIRVIN GOT SOME OF THE SUBSTANCE ON HIS HAND CAUSING A SLIGHT DISCOLORATION.  HE WAS OFFERED AND REFUSED MEDICAL TREATMENT SAYING HE FELT NO ILL EFFECTS. SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE.  THE SHIPPER WILL BE CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.
WE GOT A CALL AND I HAD MY PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT ON TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENT.  I PUT THE BOX IN THE DMP BAG AND BROUGHT TO THE CAGE AND TOOK THE STEPS NECESSARY.

AT 14:50 I RECEIVED A CALL FROM JERRY SERRA ABOUT A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE AT 28 DOOR.  I ASKED HIM WHAT THE SPILL WAS AND HE STATED THAT IT WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S.  I RESPONDED TO THE SPILL AFTER REVIEWING THE DECISION TREE AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE.  USING GOGGLES, APRON AND GLOVES AND THE DMP CART I PUT THE LEAKING IN A SPILL TUB WITH SPEEDY DRY. THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE ON THE FLOOR SO I RETURNED TO P.S.C. AT 15:00 WITH THE CONTAINED SPILL AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS FOR PROCESSING UNDER THE DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.  CLEAN UP COMPLETE AT 15:15.

TREATMENT WAS GIVEN AT WARE CO HOSPITAL.  MR DEL GIUBICE IS EMPLOYEED BY ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION (NUMBER ABOVE) (ERS) AND WAS RELEASED AFTER ER TREATMENT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE PRIMARY UNLOAD. ONE HALF GALLON OF FIVE GALLONS LEAKED DUE TO A DEFECTIVE, LOOSE FITTING LID.  THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKAGED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.  CLERK: JENI DACHSEL.

UNLOAD BROUGHT DOWN 2ND AIR TO BE PROCESSED AS DAMAGED.  I INSTRUCTED MY HELPER, TABBY GILLIGAN, TO TAKE CARE OF IT SINCE IT WAS A PRIORITY PACKAGE.  SHE OPENED THE PACKAGE AND STARTED GOING THROUGH CONTENTS AND POPCORN TO FIND DAMAGE, USING HER BARE HANDS.  SHE CAME TO BOTTLE WITH LID MISSING, PULLED IT OUT AND SHOWED IT TO ME.  THEN SAID IT WAS POISON.  I IMMEDIATELY TOLD HER TO GO UPSTAIRS AND WASH HER HANDS.  SHE DID THAT, CAME BACK DOWN AND SHOWED ME A RASH THAT HAD STARTED TO DEVELOP ON HER HAND.  I CALLED DAVE VAN DYKE OVER TO LOOK AT HER HANDS AND SUGGESTED STRONGLY SHE SEE A DOCTOR, HE AGREED.  AT THE DOCTOR'S, SHE WAS HELD FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED.  I FEEL BURGEN BURNSWIG SHOULD USE BETTER LABELING ON PACKAGES, ESPECIALLY WHEN SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THERE WAS NOTHING ON THE PACKAGE TO INDICATE IT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. IT WAS ALSO BEING SENT ALONG WITH COUGH SYRUP, WHICH IS ILLEGAL. (CONSUMABLE PRODUCT:FOOD).  CLERK: LENNIE MILLER.
NO REMARKS

AT 1600 HRS ON 1-18-94, MGR. CTS. LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY DISPATCHER MIKE CAVERHILL.  HE REPORTED THAT COFU UPCU 411296 IN CONSIST OF TRAIN XNPYR-18, LOADED WITH HAZARDOUS WASTE, SOLID, N.O.S., UN3077, (PCB'S) WAS BEING SET-OUT DUE TO LOAD SHIFT AT M.P. 426, POTTER, NE.  MR. CAVERHILL FURTHER ADVISED THAT MATERIAL WHICH HAD SHIFTED OUT OF CONTAINER WAS BROKEN CEMENT BLOCK AND WAS SECURE AND CONTAINED ON THE DECK OF THE FLATCAR WITH NO EXPOSURES TO WATERWAYS OR GROUND AS REPORTED BY THE TRAIN CREW.  ON 1-19-94, MGR. LERCH RESPONDED TO SCENE.  ON ARRIVAL, HE OBSERVED THE BOTTOM OF THE REAR DOOR OF "ROLL OFF" CONTAINER UPCU 411296 TO BE OPEN APPROXIMATELY 18 INCHES AND 2; 3 INCH WIDE METAL STRAPS WELDED TO THE DOOR AND SIDES OF CONTAINER TO SUPPORT/STABILIZE THE DOOR.  APPROXIMATELY 1/2 YARD OF BROKEN CEMENT BLOCK LAYED ON THE DECK OF FLATCAR, WEDGED BETWEEN THE OPEN DOOR AND CONTAINER UPCU 411254 LOCATED ADJACENT IT.  AT 1445HRS, MGR. LERCH CONTACTED THE WASTE GENERATOR, GENERAL MOTORS OF DETROIT, MI. AND SPOKE TO MR. JOHN DHARTE, GENERAL SUPERVISOR ENVIRONMENTAL OPERATIONS. HE ADVISED THAT THE CEMENT BLOCK HAD ENTOMBED (PCB'S) WITH A CONCENTRATION LEVEL OF 10-20 PPM AND THAT THERE SHOULD BE NO FORESEEN PROBLEMS WITH THE HANDLING AND RELOADING OF MATERIAL.  AFTER DETERMINING THAT CAR COULD BE SAFELY MOVED, MGR. LERCH HAD CAR SPOTTED AT SIDNEY, NE. WHERE LOAD COULD BE RE-ADJUSTED AND SECURED.  ON 1-20-94, MGR. LERCH CONTRACTED FILSINGER EMERGENCY SERVICES, INC...  THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM FLATCAR AND PLACED ON VISQUEEN SHEETING WITH ADDITIONAL VISQUEEN PLACED UNDER THE FLATCAR TO CONTAIN THE CEMENT BLOCKING AND PREVENT ANY CONTAMINATION WHILE CAR WAS BEING RELOADED AND ADJUSTED.  UPON COMPLETION OF LOADING CEMENT BLOCK INTO CONTAINER AND READJUSTED OF LOAD, VISQUEEN WAS PLACED IN CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL.  CONTAINER WAS THEN SECURED AND LOADED ONTO FLATCAR.  AT 1230HRS ON 1-20-93, MGR. LERCH RELEASED CAR TO DISPATCHER CAVERHILL FOR SHIPMENT.  CONTAINER MOVING UNDER HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST #3177895.  THERE WERE INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTING FROM THE INCIDENT. NOTIFICATIONS:  1400 HRS, 1-19-94, U.S.P.C.I. CUSTOMER REP., VICKI LEWIS; 1445HRS, G.M., DETROIT, WASTE GENERATOR, JOHN DHARTE, GENERAL SUPERVISOR ENVIRONMENTAL OPERATIONS; 1600 HRS, U.S.P.C.I. OPERATIONS MGR, BILL JAQUES; 1330HRS, 1-21-94, CHEM-TREC, BILL GASSON, #26563; 1345, NEBRASKA D.E.Q. JIM BOROVICH, #012194-JB-1345; 1400, U.P.R.R. EMG. MGR. STEVE MCNAUGHTON.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, VERN LIBBY RECEIVED CALL ADVISING THAT BULKTAINER UPTU 530055 PLACARED NA3082 WAS NOTED WITH A PRODUCT IN THE SPILL BOX. INSPECTION REVEALED APPROXIMATELY 1 TO 2 GALLONS OF BROWN LIQUID LYING ON BOTH SIDES OF THE  SPILL BOX PORTION OF BULKTAINER AND THE MANWAY COVER WAS NOTED SEALED.  HOWEVER, CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED ALL THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS TO BE LOOSE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK INTO THE MANWAY.  JOHN HAMMELMANN, UNOCAL KENIA, AK. WAS CONTACTED IN REGARD TO THIS INCIDENT.  HE CONTACTED DIRECTLY WITH WEST PAC ENVIRONMENTAL, SEATTLE, WA.  TOM SCHULTZ, OPERATIONS MANAGER, WEST PAC ENVIRONMENTAL INC., SEATTLE, CONTACTED THIS OFFICE REFERENCE THE LOCATION OF THE BULKTAINER. THE RAGS, BUCKETS, AND OTHER MATERIALS USED TO REPLACE THE SPILLED PRODUCT INTO BULKTAINER UPTU 530055 WERE PLACED INTO OVERPAC RECOVERY DRUMS, PROPERTY BY WEST PAC ENVIRONMENTAL INC.  BULKTAINER UPTU 530055 WAS RELEASED AT 1720HRS. 01/21/94 FOR DELIVERY.

WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTION OF TANK CAR NDYX 33803, UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER-CTS, T.M. ROBINSON DETECTED A FAINT ODOR OF AMMONIA FROM INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING OF THE CAR.  THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR WAS A SMALL VAPOR LEAK PAST THE PACKING ON THE PACKING GLAND OF THE GUAGING DEVICE.  ROBINSON WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING GLAND NUT ABOUT THREE QUARTERS OF A TURN.  THIS SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING.  THE CAR NOT DELAYED AND PROCEEDED ON IN NORMAL TRANSPORATION.  ROBINSON MADE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC. ROBINSON DID TELEPHONE MR. ROY SAVOY, MANAGER C F INDUSTRIES AT DONALDSONVILLE LOUISIANA, THE DESTINATION OF THE CAR.  SAVOY ADVISED THAT A MAINTENANCE INSPECTION WILL BE CONDUCTED ON THE GAUGING DEVICE PRIOR TO THE CAR BEING RELOADED.

column168: ON THURSDAY, 1/27/94, AFTER BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS, UPRR PERSONNEL AT ALEXANDRIA, LOUISIANA SAW WHAT APPEARED TO BE A VAPOR CLOUD COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 94420.  HOWEVER, NO ONE DETECTED THE ODOR OF AMMONIA, THERE WAS FOG IN THE AREA AND A SEVERE THUNDERSTORM  IN PROGRESS.  AS A PRECAUTION THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED.  DURING A BREAK IN THE STORM, SR. SPECIAL AGENT B.G. BAREFIELD, JR. CLIMBED THE CAR FROM THE UP WIND SIDE AND INSPECTED THE OUTSIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  BAREFIELD DID NOT HEAR OR SMELL ANY INDICATION OF A LEAK FROM THE CAR.  UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CTS T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED. AFTER CONFERRING WITH MR. ROY SAVOY OF CF INDUSTRIES, IT WAS DECIDED TO HOLD THE CAR AT ALEXANDRIA UNTIL THE MORNING OF 1/28/94.  AT THIS TIME ROBINSON WOULD CONDUCT A COMPLETE INSPECTION CHECKING FOR PROPER OUTAGE AND INTERNAL PRESSURE, TO VERIFY THAT THE CAR WAS SAFE TO CONTINUE ON IN TRANSPORATION.  ON FRIDAY, 1/28/94, AT ABOUT 1030 HOURS, ROBINSON, ASSISTED BY SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS C.D. WOMACK, REMOVED SEAL "CFI 033947" FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING OF THE CAR.  A FAINT ODOR OF AMMONIA WAS DETECTED INSIDE THE HOUSING, COMING FROM THE GAUGING DEVICE. THE GAUGING DEVICE VALVE WAS CLOSED, BUT THE QUARTER INCH PLUG WAS FINGER LOOSE.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS ALSO FINGER LOOSE.  A PRESSURE READING AT THIS LOCATION REVEALED 230 PSIG.  IN ADDITION THE CAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE 15 AND 1/2 INCHES OF OUTRAGE.  THE GAUGING DEVICE, INCLUDING PACKING GLAND NUT AND VALVE PLUG, WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED AND THE ODOR OF AMMONIA WAS GONE.  AFTER ADDITIONAL CONSULATION WITH UPRR DIRECTOR-CTS L.R. TIERNEY AND MR. SAVOY IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS SAFE TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION.  THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS SEALED WITH "MP 034499" AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO MR. MIKE CAMPBELL, UPRR MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS AT ALEXANDRIA, FOR HANDLING.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RECEIVED NOTIFICATION THAT THE SLAOZ-27 (DOUBLE STACK TRAIN) HAD DERAILED AT WEST FREMONT, CALIFORNIA.  TWO CONTAINERS HAD TOPPLED OVER THE BRIDGE AND INTO THE ALAMEDA RIVER, ONE OF WHICH WAS ON FIRE.  UPON ARRIVING FREMONT, MANAGER COOPER DEVLOPED THE SLAOZ -27 HAD BEEN MOVING IN A WESTBOUND DIRECTION AND DERAILED PRIOR TO REACHING THE RIVER BRIDGE.  UPON REACHING THE BRIDGE, THE CONTAINERS ON THE TOP OF THE DOUBLE STACK WERE SUBJECTED TO A LATERAL FORCE FROM THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE BRIDGE, CAUSING THEM TO TOPPLE INTO THE RIVER.  BASED UPON THE INFORMATION DEVELOPED FROM THE ZEP BILL OF LADING ON THE VARIOUS COMMODITIES SHIPPED AS HAZARDOUS, AND WHAT ITEMS WERE RECOVERED FROM THE RIVER BOTTOM, THE FOLLOWING REPRESENTS THE MATERIALS SLOST DUE TO THE RUPTURED CONTAINERS OR DESTROYED DUE TO THE FIRE.  ALL RECOVERED COMMODITIES LISTED AS HAZARDOUS WERE PLACED IN OVERPACKS BY HAZARD GROUPS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AS THE CONSIGNEE REJECTED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE LADING. THE REMAINING ITEMS BURNED IN THE FIRE WERE ALSO PLACED INTO ROLL OFF BINS PENDING CLASSIFICATION FOR DISPOSAL.
